revision.text:
{{short description|Rare genetic disease affecting palate, thumbs, and upper limbs}} {{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Adducted thumb syndrome | synonyms = Christian syndrome, craniostenosis arthrogryposis cleft palate | image = Image:autorecessive.svg | caption = Adducted thumb syndrome has a lysosomal recessive pattern of inheritance | meshName = | meshNumber = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Adducted thumb syndrome recessive form''' is a [[rare disease]] affecting multiple systems causing malformations of the palate, thumbs, and upper limbs. The name Christian syndrome derives from Joe. C. Christian, the first person to describe the condition. Inheritance is believed to be [[autosomal recessive]],<ref name=Fitch>{{cite journal |vauthors=Fitch N, Levy EP |title=Adducted thumb syndromes |journal=Clin. Genet. |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=190–8 |year=1975 |pmid=1175322 |doi= 10.1111/j.1399-0004.1975.tb01493.x|url=}}</ref> caused by mutation in the [[CHST14]] (carbohydrate sulfotransferase 14) gene.<ref name=NCBI> {{cite web |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene?Db=gene&Cmd=ShowDetailView&TermToSearch=113189 |title=CHST14 |work=[[National Center for Biotechnology Information]] database |publisher=NCBI |accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref>
==Signs and symptoms== This syndrome is characterised by typical facial appearance, slight build, thin and translucent skin, severely adducted thumbs, [[arachnodactyly]], [[Club foot|club feet]], joint instability, [[facial cleft]]ing and bleeding disorders, as well as heart, kidney or intestinal defects. Severe [[Psychomotor learning|psychomotor]] and developmental delay and decreased muscle tone may also be present during infancy. Cognitive development during childhood is normal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rarediseases.info.nih.gov/GARD/QnASelected.aspx?diseaseID=8486|title=Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, musculocontractural type – Genetic and Rare Diseases Information Center (GARD) – an NCATS Program|publisher=}}</ref>
==Cause== {{Empty section|date=April 2017}}
==Diagnosis== This syndrome is associated with [[microcephaly]], [[arthrogryposis]] and [[cleft palate]] and various craniofacial, respiratory, neurological and limb abnormalities, including [[bone]] and [[joint]] defects of the upper limbs, [[Adduction|adducted]] thumbs, [[camptodactyly]] and [[talipes equinovarus]] or calcaneovalgus. It is characterized by craniosynostosis, and myopathy in association with congenital generalized [[hypertrichosis]].<ref name="Bolognia">{{cite book |author =Rapini, Ronald P. |author2 =Bolognia, Jean L. |author3 =Jorizzo, Joseph L. |title=Dermatology: 2-Volume Set |publisher=Mosby |location=St. Louis |year=2007 |pages=1008 |isbn=1-4160-2999-0 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref> Patients with the disease are considered [[intellectual disability|intellectually disabled]]. Most die in childhood. Patients often suffer from respiratory difficulties such as [[pneumonia]], and from [[seizures]] due to dysmyelination in the brain's [[white matter]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kunze J, Park W, Hansen KH, Hanefeld F |title=Adducted thumb syndrome. Report of a new case and a diagnostic approach |journal=Eur. J. Pediatr. |volume=141 |issue=2 |pages=122–6 |year=1983 |pmid=6662143 |doi= 10.1007/BF00496805|url=}}</ref> It has been hypothesized that the [[Moro reflex]] (startle reflex in infants) may be a tool in detecting the congenital clapsed thumb early in infancy.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Anderson TE, Breed AL | year = 1981 | title = Congenital clasped thumb and the Moro reflex. (Letter) | url = | journal = [[The Journal of Pediatrics]] | volume = 99 | issue = | pages = 664–665 | doi=10.1016/s0022-3476(81)80293-4}}</ref> The thumb normally extends as a result of this reflex.
==Treatment== {{Empty section|date=April 2017}}
