{{COI|date=July 2017}} {{Infobox organization |image = |alt = |caption = |map = |motto = |formation = |extinction = |type = |status = |purpose = [[AIDS]] research |headquarters = |language = |leader_title = Director |leader_name = [[Salim Abdool Karim]] |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |budget = |remarks = |name = CAPRISA |image_border = |size = |msize = |malt = |mcaption = |abbreviation = |location = [[Durban]], [[South Africa]] |region_served = |membership = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |website = http://www.caprisa.org/ }}
'''CAPRISA''' ("'''Centre for the AIDS Programme of Research in South Africa'''") is the name of an [[AIDS]] research center based in [[Durban]], [[South Africa]].
==History== CAPRISA was established in 2002 under the [[National Institutes of Health]] program called [[Comprehensive International Program of Research on AIDS]] (CIPRA). Five partner institutions participated in the founding: [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]], [[University of Cape Town]], [[University of Western Cape]], [[National Institute of Communicable Diseases]], and [[Columbia University]] in [[New York City|New York]]. [[UNAIDS]] recognizes CAPRISA with the designation of "Collaborating Centre for HIV Prevention Research."<ref name="founding">{{cite web |url=http://www.caprisa.org/SitePages/About-Founding.aspx |title=Founding of CAPRISA |author= |date= |work= |publisher=CAPRISA |accessdate=23 January 2011}}</ref>
CAPRISA's mission is to promote HIV prevention and research its epidemiology.<ref name="founding"/>
==CAPRISA 004== {{Main|CAPRISA 004}}
[[CAPRISA 004]] is the name of a [[clinical trial]] testing a [[microbicide]] which was experimentally shown to be effective in reducing women's risk of contracting HIV.<ref>{{cite news |title=African Studies Give Women Hope in H.I.V. Fight |author=Celia W. Dugger |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/20/world/africa/20safrica.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=19 July 2010 |accessdate=23 January 2011}}</ref>
