'''Computer-adaptive sequential testing''' ('''CAST''') is another term for [[multistage testing]]. A CAST test is a type of [[computer-adaptive test]] or [[computerized classification test]] that uses pre-defined groups of items called ''[[testlet]]s'' rather than operating at the level of individual items.<ref>Luecht, R.M. (2005). Some useful cost-benefit criteria for evaluating computer-based test delivery models and systems. ''Journal of Applied Testing Technology, 7''(2). {{cite web |url=http://www.testpublishers.org/Documents/JATT2005_rev_Criteria4CBT_RMLuecht_Apr2005.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-12-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927064953/http://www.testpublishers.org/Documents/JATT2005_rev_Criteria4CBT_RMLuecht_Apr2005.pdf |archivedate=2006-09-27 |df= }}</ref> CAST is a term introduced by [[psychometrics|psychometricians]] working for the National Board of Medical Examiners.<ref>Luecht, R. M. & Nungester, R. J. (1998). Some practical examples of computer-adaptive sequential testing. Journal of Educational Measurement, 35, 229–249.</ref> In CAST, the testlets are referred to as ''panels''.
