{{Orphan|date=September 2016}}
'''Jean Evelyn Headberry''' (1911–1993) was an Australian registered nurse and [[midwife]] who was awarded the [[Florence Nightingale Medal]] in 1961.<ref name="Google News Archive Search 1961">{{cite web | title=The Age | website=Google News Archive Search | date=1961-07-20 | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1300&dat=19610720&id=-7AUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hLoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3911,2835400&hl=en | accessdate=2016-09-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/frd/Military_Law/pdf/RC_May-1962.pdf |title=International Review of the Red Cross, May 1962, Second year - No. 14 |format=PDF |website=Loc.gov |date= |accessdate=2016-12-07}}</ref> Headberry served as an [[Army nurse]] during [[World War II]].<ref name="Australian War Memorial">{{cite web | title=AUSTRALIAN NURSES ABOUT TO EMBARK (EMBARKATION "G" ) FOR OVERSEAS SERVICE. MATRON IN CHIEF GRACE WILSON CBE RRC (LOWER LEFT) FAREWELLED THE NURSING CONTINGENT. STANDING ABOVE HER (FROM THE TOP OF ... | website=Australian War Memorial | url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/003068/01/ | accessdate=2016-09-08}}</ref><ref name="McCullagh 2010 p. 89">{{cite book | last=McCullagh | first=C. | title=Willingly Into the Fray: One Hundred Years of Australian Army Nursing | publisher=Big Sky Publishing Pty, Limited | series=Australian Army history collection | year=2010 | isbn=978-0-9806582-6-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0bHdFjRn2H0C&pg=PT89 | accessdate=2016-09-08 | page=89}}</ref> She later became the Dean of Royal Melbourne and Associated Hospital's School of Nursing.<ref name="Google News Archive Search 1961"/><ref name="Wilkinson 2000">{{cite book | last=Wilkinson | first=J. | title="You Would Not be Suitable as a Nurse, Dear": Jean Evelyn Headberry, FNM 1911-1993 : a Biography | publisher=Melbourne School of Nursing Past Trainees Association | year=2000 | isbn=978-0-9589683-1-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Kd0PQAACAAJ | accessdate=2016-09-08}}</ref>

